1. Water & Boat visuals
Goal: Keep the paper‑boat Spline as the main ambient element, but add a fluid, watery feel and gentle motion.

1.1 Animated mesh‑style gradient behind the boat
Add a slow animated gradient layer behind the Spline iframe to suggest water, without overpowering the content.

css
.hero-section {
position: relative;
overflow: hidden;
width: 100%;
min-height: 100vh;
background: radial-gradient(circle at 20% 20%, #eef1ff 0, #ffffff 45%, #f4f7ff 100%);
}

/* Mesh-like animated gradient */
.hero-section::before {
content: '';
position: absolute;
inset: -20%;
background:
radial-gradient(circle at 10% 20%, rgba(120, 132, 255, 0.28), transparent 55%),
radial-gradient(circle at 80% 10%, rgba(130, 220, 255, 0.24), transparent 55%),
radial-gradient(circle at 50% 90%, rgba(180, 150, 255, 0.25), transparent 55%);
animation: meshDrift 30s ease-in-out infinite alternate;
z-index: 0;
pointer-events: none;
}
@keyframes meshDrift {
0% { transform: translate3d(0, 0, 0); }
50% { transform: translate3d(-40px, 20px, 0); }
100% { transform: translate3d(30px, -30px, 0); }
}
This sits under your cards and under (or behind) the Spline boat, giving a slow liquid feel.
​

1.2 Paper boat float + parallax
Wrap the Spline iframe in a boat-layer that floats up/down and reacts slightly to mouse movement on desktop.

xml
<div class="spline-background">
    <div class="boat-layer">
        <iframe src="https://my.spline.design/animatedpaperboat-jeJTnCRZkUeZW3jf48yUoDEa/" frameborder="0" width="100%"
            height="100%">
        </iframe>
    </div>
</div>
css
.boat-layer {
position: absolute;
inset: 0;
animation: boatFloat 8s ease-in-out infinite alternate;
will-change: transform;
}
@keyframes boatFloat {
0% { transform: translateY(0px); }
100% { transform: translateY(-10px); } /* 5–10px gentle bob */
}
javascript
// Subtle parallax on desktop
const boatLayer = document.querySelector('.boat-layer');
window.addEventListener('mousemove', (e) => {
const x = (e.clientX / window.innerWidth - 0.5) * 10; // -5 to +5
const y = (e.clientY / window.innerHeight - 0.5) * 6; // -3 to +3
boatLayer.style.transform = `translate3d(${x}px, ${y - 5}px, 0)`; // keep float offset
});
For mobile, you can skip the mouse parallax and rely only on boatFloat.

